AGI - There will be the crisis in the Middle East - after <a href="https://www.agi.it/estero/news/2024-04-13/iran-lancia-decine-droni-israel-attack-netanyahu-idf-ultime-notizie-26015609/"> the Saturday attack of Iran to Israel</a>, the fear of a further escalation
&nbsp;
Italy, current president of turn of the G7, pushes for de-escalation and peace, as yesterday repeated the head of diplomacy, Antonio Tajani>; and is open to new sanctions to Iran. The United States has also announced that they are studying with the G7 allies further sanctions to the ayatollah regime to contain its drone and missile program. And the Canadian Foreign Minister, Melanie Joly, just before leaving Italy, anticipated that among the themes to be discussed there will be to "impose more sanctions against the Iranian regime".
&nbsp;
Tajani has announced that Italy is also ready to send military personnel to the area in the framework of an UN mission if a Palestinian state was created. "While there should be Onu a bearing presence, when there will be two peoples and two states, we are ready to participate. A Unifil-type presence - the United Nations' interposition force in Lebanon - to ensure peace and stability in a mission under the auspices of the UN as an Arab guide". The objective 'two peoples two states', insisted, "remains the polar star, but they recognize each other. It's not an easy goal but we'll get it all."
&nbsp;
Tajani met yesterday representatives of the Arab League and the Organization of Islamic Cooperation to discuss the crisis in the Middle East and "why dialogue wins". The meeting with ambassadors "was focused on the will of dialogue and stability" in the Middle East, "on the humanitarian crisis in Gaza" and on the condemnation of any form of retaliation and aggression that could lead to a dramatic escalation in the region," announced the Foreign Ministry in a note. Tajani emphasized that "in a context of strong escalation, in which every further hostile act could trigger a wider conflict that could affect the entire region", Italy "is doing everything possible to invite all actors of the region to moderation, also as G7 Presidency".
&nbsp;
In Capri, in addition to the Group's foreign ministers (France, Japan, Germany, Canada, the United States and the United Kingdom, as well as Italy) the Mauritanian Foreign Minister was invited, who at this time has the presidency of the African Union. The meeting will also be attended by the High Representative for Foreign Affairs and Security Policy of the European Union, Josep Borrell>, and the Secretary General of NATO, Jens Stoltenberg>. On the agenda, of course, also the themes of the Red Sea and Ukraine, a country which will be represented by the Foreign Minister, Dmitry Kouleba>.

